------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Third-party engine techniques
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Membrillo adapted several presentation techniques from the "pointclick-adventure"
Claude skill by AngelJaimer:

    https://github.com/AngelJaimer/pointclick-adventure

That kit's README grants reuse ("The engine itself is yours to reuse."). With
thanks, the following FOUR presentation modules adapted techniques from it. The
list is precise so the reused portions could be isolated or replaced if ever
needed (a fuller diff is in docs/2026-07-19-kit-reuse-audit.md):

  - packages/membrillo/art/dither.ts — DERIVED. The ordered (Bayer 4x4)
    dithering API and algorithm: ditherPick, rampPick, the Pixels ImageData
    wrapper, and the (BAYER4[y][x] + 0.5) / 16 threshold. Reimplemented and
    re-commented; rampRect is our addition.
  - packages/membrillo/art/sprites.ts — PARTIAL. Only the pixel-draw helpers
    px() and blk() (blk = a 1px-outlined rect) and the left/right mirror trick
    (faceCtx), from the kit's art/actor.ts. drawActor, the walkFrame gait,
    Pose, talkMouth, blinking, and portraits are ours.
  - packages/membrillo/audio/engine.ts — PARTIAL. The "themes as data"
    model (bpm / progression / scale / style / gain) and the Web Audio
    lookahead-scheduler + fail-silent architecture. Voices/synthesis are
    reimplemented and simpler.
  - packages/membrillo/art/palette.ts — IDIOM ONLY. The "one small shared
    palette, every colour picked from it" pattern (a P object of named RGB
    tuples). The colours and names themselves are ours.

Everything else is original to Membrillo (much of the rules model carried over
from the earlier tng-game, not the kit): the model-checked rules core and
fuzzer, the JSON story data model, the three-verb interaction model, walkboxes
+ pathfinding, the scrolling camera, followers, the loader/boot seam, the
render layer, the Pixel Operator text (not the kit's code bitmap font), the
offline tools and CLI, and all story content. The kit is reference only —
never a code dependency, and nothing from it ships at runtime.
